 High-level Kubernetes Architecture
At the highest level, Kubernetes has two major parts:
•	Control Plane (Master) – the brain 🧠
•	Worker Nodes – where your apps actually run 
                ┌────────────────────────┐
                │     Control Plane      │
                │  (Kubernetes Master)   │
                └──────────┬─────────────┘
                           │
        ┌──────────────────┴──────────────────┐
        │                                     │
┌───────────────┐                    ┌───────────────┐
│  Worker Node  │                    │  Worker Node  │
│   (Node 1)    │                    │   (Node 2)    │
└───────────────┘                    └───────────────┘
________________________________________
Control Plane Components (The Brain)
The Control Plane makes all decisions in the cluster.
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              CONTROL PLANE                   │
│                                              │
│  ┌──────────┐   ┌────────────┐   ┌─────────┐ │
│  │ API      │   │ Scheduler  │   │ etcd    │ │
│  │ Server   │   │            │   │         │ │
│  └──────────┘   └────────────┘   └─────────┘ │
│        │               │               │     │
│  ┌────────────┐   ┌──────────────┐           │
│  │ Controller │   │ Cloud        │           │
│  │ Manager    │   │ Controller   │           │
│  └────────────┘   └──────────────┘           │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘

API Server
•	Entry point to Kubernetes
•	All commands (kubectl, CI/CD, UI) talk to it
•	Validates & processes requests
No component talks to another directly — everything goes via the API server

🔹 etcd
•	Distributed key-value store
•	Stores cluster state:
	a)Pods
	b)Secrets
	c)ConfigMaps
	d)Node info
🛑 If etcd is lost, the cluster is lost.

🔹 Scheduler
•	Decides which node a Pod runs on
•	Considers:
	a) CPU & memory
    b) Node taints & tolerations
	c) Affinity rules

🔹 Controller Manager
Ensures desired state = actual state
Examples:
•	Node Controller
•	ReplicaSet Controller
•	Deployment Controller
“You want 3 replicas? I’ll keep creating Pods until you have 3.”

🔹 Cloud Controller Manager (Optional)
•	Talks to cloud providers (AWS, GCP, Azure)
•	Manages:
o	Load Balancers
o	Volumes
o	Node lifecycle
